### Describe the bug

Maybe this is actually a feature, but it has potentially some serious unintended consequences, so I'm filing it as a bug. 

If a project has **operative code that executes during startup**, Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Server 9.0.2 executes that code by simply **building** the project. I've only tried building it using Visual Studio 2022.

I'll try to attach the full sample code, but I'm also including the Program.cs below, where a table should be created in the local Storage Account emulator during **runtime** startup of the project. But by simply adding Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Server 9.0.2 to the project, simply **building** the project will **execute** the creation of the table. That can't be right.

```
using Azure.Data.Tables;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Azure;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

builder.Services.AddAzureClients(clientBuilder =>
{
	var tableConfigSection = builder.Configuration.GetSection("MyStorageTable");
	clientBuilder.AddTableServiceClient(tableConfigSection).WithName("MyStorageTable");
});

var app = builder.Build();

using (var scope = app.Services.CreateAsyncScope())
{
	var tableClientFactory = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<IAzureClientFactory<TableServiceClient>>();
	var tableServiceClient = tableClientFactory.CreateClient("MyStorageTable");

	// When Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Server 9.0.2 exists in this project,
	// this table below will be CREATED simply by BUILDING the project.
	//
	// You don't even have to RUN the project to have the table created, the ApiDescription Server
	// will EXECUTE your project during build, and as such run the CreateTableAsync.
	//
	// The project will not actually finish building, you'll get two errors related to the 
	// ApiDescription Server, but by that time the project has already executed CreateTableAsync
	// 
	// You'll get the same issue if you use IHostedService and AddHostedService btw.
	//
	var response = await tableServiceClient.CreateTableAsync("ThisTableIsCreatedWhenBUILDINGTheProject");
}

app.MapOpenApi();

app.MapGet("/", () => Results.Redirect("/CurrentLevelOfIncompetence"));
app.MapGet("/CurrentLevelOfIncompetence", () =>
{
	var levels = new[]
	{
		"Noticeable", "Concerning", "Severe", "Alarming", "Dismal", "Catastrophic", "Mind-Boggling", "Unforgivable", "Staggering"
	};
	return "Current level of incompetence: " + levels[Random.Shared.Next(levels.Length)];
});

app.Run();
```

